annotation.TEXT: Well, let's bust out of here...
Now he's got two Railroads?! Come on!
I'll just unlock the door with my butt, because I'm that awesome!
Of course, the one on the next street is another story...
Okay, that's good!
Well, a least I'll pass Go no matter what I roll...
And meanwhile, I'm just getting "Railroaded".
Really? Income Tax already? Well, since the game just started, I'll just pay the 10%.
Wow... That really sucks.
OH, COME ON! Seriously?!
Oh, and there's my 5...

Looks like I got off that piece of land just in time!

And of course, my opponent gets the Railroad...
Now, I'm not going to waste too much time talking. If King Lorik's speech is too fast for you to read, pause the video.
Have you ever had one of those days, where no matter what you do, nothing seems to go right for you?
Nuts!
Well, I know Boardwalk's rent is $50, which will end me, so just avoid rolling a 4, and I'll survive.
Come to mock me, Arthur?
"Don't be coming back now."
Yep, he's getting all the good cards today.
I'll just play a simple 2 player game and give Luigi another chance here.
Let's try something entirely different.
Let me run, dang it!

Well, this isn't going well...
Let's try again.

Alright, now let's raid the treasure!
To not be continued...

Ooh, I landed on Boardwalk before Arthur got to it!
One of which I land on immediately afterwards. (Well... It's not as bad as a Railroad.)
Now, to begin with, I want to head to the neighboring town of Brecconary to purchase equipment. Hopefully, I can get there without getting attacked...
Grumble.. Grumble... Well, if you end up in jail early in the game, it's often best to get out of there immediately.
Wow. Is it just me, or is Arthur having incredible luck today?
Alright! I get to go first!
D'oh!
Seriously, I'm down to my last hit point! If I fail to run again, I'm doomed!
Oh, crap!
...Or not.
Nothing fancy, let's just play a basic game.
It figures...
Of course, the computer never gets three doubles in a row, just three properties in a row.
Crap, I forgot about the Luxury Tax! NOOOOO!!!!!
Alright, there's no way I can hit that Railroad right in front of me!
Ow!!! That was just... bad!
...And everything seems to go right for your opponent(s)?
Thou art slimed.
First, let's start off by entering a name. Interestingly, your name has an effect on your character's stats. If you want details on how this works, check out GameFAQs.
Yay, money!
I don't think I have any spells or items that can help out, so all I can do is attack.
And of course, go with a fast message speed since we don't want to be here all day.
Okay, this being the first battle in the game, it's very simple. Just keep attacking.
Whew, no doubles. I was afraid... What?!
Oh, come on. Hit the guy already!
Uh, oh! A red slime! I should probably run, but... I think I can take him!
I've got nothing...
And a torch, which will allow me to see where I'm going in a dark cave.
...And hopefully, you won't miss...
And here I thought this game was supposed to be easy!
But... I don't have enough money!!! No... I have to auction it, which means...
Ah, yes. Good ol' Monopoly! You can't die to a monster here (I don't think)!
Let's give Luigi a chance to redeem himself here. (I don't think name affects stats in this game, though.)
And, most importantly, the magic key, which is needed to get out of the throne room, so I can begin my adventure!
By the way, I'm not going to spend time talking to everyone. I just want to get to the action! If you want to hear what they all say, play the game yourself, or watch someone else's LP of this game.
Arrgh!!! And of course I'd land on the one he just purchased...

FFMQ has an interesting mechanic that not all RPGs possess: You can jump over obstacles while on the field. It's very handy when a random NPC wanders into a narrow path you need to travel down or something!
...If the game'll let me!
Whew... Oh, no! NOOOOO!!!!!
Wow... Am I doing something wrong?
As for my opponent, I think I'll choose Arthur. He seems nice enough.
Okay, maybe Dragon Warrior is just not my thing today. Let's try another RPG.
Okay, forget it. I'm just going to run.
Well, it's still my turn...
